  "secText": [
    "  <b>Supplemental Material:</b> Advanced Math",
    "  <b>Essential Question: </b>  <b>    <br />  </b>How can we multiply a rectangular vector by a scalar?",
    "  <b>Enduring Understandings:</b>  <b>    <br />  </b>1. To <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='4' data-topic='5' data-subtopic='1'>multiply a vector by a scalar</a> graphically, increase the length of the vector by the product of the vector and scalar.<b><br /></b>2. To <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='4' data-topic='5' data-subtopic='2'>multiply a vector by a scalar numerically</a>, multiply the scalar by each vector component.<b><br /></b>3. Vectors can be written in <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='4' data-topic='5' data-subtopic='3'>polar form</a> by using the length of the vector and the angle made with the positive <i>x</i>-axis.<b><br /></b>4. To <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='4' data-topic='5' data-subtopic='4'>multiply a polar vector by a scalar numerically</a>, multiply the magnitude of the vector by the absolute value of the scalar. If the scalar is positive, the angle remains the same. If the scalar is negative, add 180° to the angle.",
    "  <b>Vocabulary:</b>  <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='4' data-topic='5' data-subtopic='1'>multiplying a vector</a>, <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='4' data-topic='5' data-subtopic='3'>vector (polar)</a>, <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='4' data-topic='5' data-subtopic='4'>multiplying a polar vector by a scalar</a>",
